  volume = {191},
  number = {15},
  pages = {3501--3523},
  doi = {10.1007/s11229-014-0418-1},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: King develops an account of intellectual perseverance as a virtue,
  distinct from but related to other intellectual virtues like conscientiousness,
  honesty, courage, and open-mindedness. Intellectual perseverance involves
  sustained engagement with difficult intellectual tasks despite obstacles,
  setbacks, and temptations to give up. King argues that intellectual perseverance
  is valuable both instrumentally (it helps achieve truth) and constitutively (it
  reflects proper valuation of intellectual goods).

  RELEVANCE: While not directly about honesty or integrity, King's analysis of
  intellectual perseverance connects to literature review ethics in important ways.
  Comprehensive literature engagement requires perseverance—the willingness to
  continue searching, reading, and synthesizing even when it becomes tedious or
  overwhelming. King's work suggests that virtuous scholarship involves not just
  avoiding dishonesty but also cultivating the stamina to pursue thorough
  understanding. This virtue-theoretic framework complements duty-based accounts by
  highlighting the dispositional qualities that enable responsible scholarship.

  POSITION: Virtue-theoretic account of intellectual perseverance as essential for
  sustained inquiry; complements other intellectual virtues in enabling good
  scholarship.
  },
  keywords = {intellectual-virtue, perseverance, virtue-epistemology, Medium, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

